<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-314-918  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 314 918.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Computer Graphics and Applications  March 1990 v10 n2 p62(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A general algorithm for oblique image reconstruction. (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kramer, David M.; Kaufman, Leon; Guzman, Ricardo J.; Hawryszko,Christine.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Reconstructing, or reformatting, oblique two-dimensional imagesfrom a three-dimensional set of starting images is a commonclinical radiological problem.andP;  A general oblique reconstructionalgorithm is presented that preserves the volume resolution of theoriginal data set and that has been used to create oblique planarslices and slices along curved surfaces.andP;  The algorithm is basedon the Fourier-shift theorem, which states that a shifted datafunction can be produced through a convolution with a deltafunction displaced from the origin by the amount of the desiredshift.andP;  The algorithm is efficient for calculating large numbersof slices; examples are provided showing how well suited thealgorithm is for three-dimensional magnetic resonance images.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Three-Dimensional GraphicsMedical DiagnosisImaging TechnologyImage ReconstructionNew TechniqueAlgorithm AnalysisTheoretical ResearchClinical MedicineRadiology.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   A generalized oblique &quot;plane&quot; using only 1D moves along theprimary axis. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>